.TH "Node.firstChild" "JS" "April 7, 2023" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Node.firstChild \- Node: firstChild property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The read\-only \f[B]\f[CB]firstChild\f[B]\f[R] property of the
\f[CR]Node\f[R] interface returns the node\[cq]s first child in the
tree, or \f[CR]null\f[R] if the node has no children.
.PP
If the node is a \f[CR]Document\f[R], this property returns the first
node in the list of its direct children.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This property returns any type of node that is the first
child of this one.
It may be a \f[CR]Text\f[R] or a \f[CR]Comment\f[R] node.
If you want to get the first \f[CR]Element\f[R] that is a child of
another element, consider using \f[CR]Element.firstElementChild\f[R].
.RE
.SH VALUE
A \f[CR]Node\f[R], or \f[CR]null\f[R] if there are none.
.SH EXAMPLE
This example demonstrates the use of \f[CR]firstChild\f[R] and how
whitespace nodes might interfere with using this property.
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]p\f[R] id=\[dq]para\-01\[dq]>
  <\f[B]span\f[R]>First span</\f[B]span\f[R]>
</\f[B]p\f[R]>

<\f[B]script\f[R]>
  \f[B]const\f[R] p01 = document.getElementById(\[dq]para\-01\[dq]);
  console.log(p01.firstChild.nodeName);
</\f[B]script\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
In the above, the console will show `#text' because a text node is
inserted to maintain the whitespace between the end of the opening
\f[CR]<p>\f[R] and \f[CR]<span>\f[R] tags.
\f[B]Any\f[R] whitespace will create a \f[CR]#text\f[R] node, from a
single space to multiple spaces, returns, tabs, and so on.
.PP
Another \f[CR]#text\f[R] node is inserted between the closing
\f[CR]</span>\f[R] and \f[CR]</p>\f[R] tags.
.PP
If this whitespace is removed from the source, the #text nodes are not
inserted and the span element becomes the paragraph\[cq]s first child.
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]p\f[R] id=\[dq]para\-01\[dq]><\f[B]span\f[R]>First span</\f[B]span\f[R]></\f[B]p\f[R]>

<\f[B]script\f[R]>
  \f[B]const\f[R] p01 = document.getElementById(\[dq]para\-01\[dq]);
  console.log(p01.firstChild.nodeName);
</\f[B]script\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
Now the console will show `SPAN'.
.PP
To avoid the issue with \f[CR]node.firstChild\f[R] returning
\f[CR]#text\f[R] or \f[CR]#comment\f[R] nodes,
\f[CR]Element.firstElementChild\f[R] can be used to return only the
first element node.
